# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actuarial-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuaries are professionals trained in this discipline.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In many countries, actuaries must demonstrate their competence by passing a series of rigorous professional examinations focused in fields such as probability and predictive analysis.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] News & World Report*, their job often has to do with using mathematics to identify risk so they can mitigate risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial science includes a number of interrelated subjects, including mathematics, probability theory, statistics, finance, economics, financial accounting and computer science.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Historically, actuarial science used deterministic models in the construction of tables and premiums.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The science has gone through revolutionary changes since the 1980s due to the proliferation of high speed computers and the union of stochastic actuarial models with modern financial theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Many universities have undergraduate and graduate degree programs in actuarial science.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In 2010, a study published by job search website CareerCast ranked actuary as the #1 job in the United States.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The study used five key criteria to rank jobs: environment, income, employment outlook, physical demands, and stress.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] News & World Report* ranked actuary as the third-best job in the business sector and the eighth-best job in STEM.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial science became a formal mathematical discipline in the late 17th century with the increased demand for long-term insurance coverage such as burial, life insurance, and annuities.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] These long term coverages required that money be set aside to pay future benefits, such as annuity and death benefits many years into the future.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] This requires estimating future contingent events, such as the rates of mortality by age, as well as the development of mathematical techniques for discounting the value of funds set aside and invested.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] This led to the development of an important actuarial concept, referred to as the present value of a future sum.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Certain aspects of the actuarial methods for discounting pension funds have come under criticism from modern financial economics.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial science is also applied to property, casualty, liability, and general insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In these forms of insurance, coverage is generally provided on a renewable period (such as a yearly).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Coverage can be cancelled at the end of the period by either party.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Property and casualty insurance companies tend to specialize because of the complexity and diversity of risks.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] One division is to organize around personal and commercial lines of insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Personal lines of insurance are for individuals and include fire, auto, homeowners, theft, and umbrella coverages.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Commercial lines address the insurance needs of businesses and include property, business continuation, product liability, fleet/commercial vehicle, workers compensation, fidelity and surety, and D&O insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The insurance industry also provides coverage for exposures such as catastrophe, weather-related risks, earthquakes, patent infringement and other forms of corporate espionage, terrorism, and "one-of-a-kind" (e.g., satellite launch).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial science provides data collection, measurement, estimating, forecasting, and valuation tools to provide financial and underwriting data for management to assess marketing opportunities and the nature of the risks.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial science often helps to assess the overall risk from catastrophic events in relation to its underwriting capacity or surplus.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In the reinsurance fields, actuarial science can be used to design and price reinsurance and retrocession arrangements, and to establish reserve funds for known claims and future claims and catastrophes.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] There is an increasing trend to recognize that actuarial skills can be applied to a range of applications outside the traditional fields of insurance, pensions, etc.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] One notable example is the use in some US states of actuarial models to set criminal sentencing guidelines.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] These models attempt to predict the chance of re-offending according to rating factors which include the type of crime, age, educational background and ethnicity of the offender.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] However, these models have been open to criticism as providing justification for discrimination against specific ethnic groups by law enforcement personnel.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Whether this is statistically correct or a self-fulfilling correlation remains under debate.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Another example is the use of actuarial models to assess the risk of sex offense recidivism.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial models and associated tables, such as the MnSOST-R, Static-99, and SORAG, have been used since the late 1990s to determine the likelihood that a sex offender will re-offend and thus whether he or she should be institutionalized or set free.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Traditional actuarial science and modern financial economics in the US have different practices, which is caused by different ways of calculating funding and investment strategies, and by different regulations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Historically, much of the foundation of actuarial theory predated modern financial theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In the early twentieth century, actuaries were developing many techniques that can be found in modern financial theory, but for various historical reasons, these developments did not achieve much recognition.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] As a result, actuarial science developed along a different path, becoming more reliant on assumptions, as opposed to the arbitrage-free risk-neutral valuation concepts used in modern finance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The divergence is not related to the use of historical data and statistical projections of liability cash flows, but is instead caused by the manner in which traditional actuarial methods apply market data with those numbers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] For example, one traditional actuarial method suggests that changing the mix of investments can change the value of liabilities and assets (by changing the discount rate assumption).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] This concept is inconsistent with financial economics.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The potential of modern financial economics theory to complement existing actuarial science was recognized by actuaries in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, there was a distinct effort for actuaries to combine financial theory and stochastic methods into their established models.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Ideas from financial economics became increasingly influential in actuarial thinking, and actuarial science has started to embrace more sophisticated mathematical modelling of finance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Today, the profession, both in practice and in the educational syllabi of many actuarial organizations, is cognizant of the need to reflect the combined approach of tables, loss models, stochastic methods, and financial theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] However, assumption-dependent concepts are still widely used (such as the setting of the discount rate assumption as mentioned earlier), particularly in North America.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Product design adds another dimension to the debate.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Financial economists argue that pension benefits are bond-like and should not be funded with equity investments without reflecting the risks of not achieving expected returns.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] But some pension products do reflect the risks of unexpected returns.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In some cases, the pension beneficiary assumes the risk, or the employer assumes the risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] 2. assets and liabilities with identical cash flows should have the same price.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] 3. the value of an asset is independent of its financing.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Essentially, financial economics state that pension assets should not be invested in equities for a variety of theoretical and practical reasons.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Elementary mutual aid agreements and pensions arose in antiquity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Early in the Roman Empire, associations were formed to meet the expenses of burial, cremation, and monuments—precursors to burial insurance and friendly societies.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] A small sum was paid into a communal fund on a weekly basis, and upon the death of a member, the fund would cover the expenses of rites and burial.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] These societies sometimes sold shares in the building of columbāria, or burial vaults, owned by the fund—the precursor to mutual insurance companies.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Other early examples of mutual surety and assurance pacts can be traced back to various forms of fellowship within the Saxon clans of England and their Germanic forebears, and to Celtic society.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] However, many of these earlier forms of surety and aid would often fail due to lack of understanding and knowledge.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The 17th century was a period of advances in mathematics in Germany, France and England.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] At the same time there was a rapidly growing desire and need to place the valuation of personal risk on a more scientific basis.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Independently of each other, compound interest was studied and probability theory emerged as a well-understood mathematical discipline.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Another important advance came in 1662 from a London draper, the father of demography, John Graunt, who showed that there were predictable patterns of longevity and death in a group, or cohort, of people of the same age, despite the uncertainty of the date of death of any one individual.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] This study became the basis for the original life table.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] One could now set up an insurance scheme to provide life insurance or pensions for a group of people, and to calculate with some degree of accuracy how much each person in the group should contribute to a common fund assumed to earn a fixed rate of interest.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The first person to demonstrate publicly how this could be done was Edmond Halley (of Halley's Comet fame).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Halley constructed his own life table, and showed how it could be used to calculate the premium amount someone of a given age should pay to purchase a life annuity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] James Dodson's pioneering work on the long term insurance contracts under which the same premium is charged each year led to the formation of the Society for Equitable Assurances on Lives and Survivorship (now commonly known as Equitable Life) in London in 1762.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] William Morgan is often considered the father of modern actuarial science for his work in the field in the 1780s and 90s.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Many other life insurance companies and pension funds were created over the following 200 years.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Equitable Life was the first to use the word "actuary" for its chief executive officer in 1762.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Previously, "actuary" meant an official who recorded the decisions, or "acts", of ecclesiastical courts.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Other companies that did not use such mathematical and scientific methods most often failed or were forced to adopt the methods pioneered by Equitable.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In the 18th and 19th centuries, calculations were performed without computers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuarial organizations were founded to support and further both actuaries and actuarial science, and to protect the public interest by promoting competency and ethical standards.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] However, calculations remained cumbersome, and actuarial shortcuts were commonplace.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Non-life actuaries followed in the footsteps of their life insurance colleagues during the 20th century.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The 1920 revision for the New-York based National Council on Workmen's Compensation Insurance rates took over two months of around-the-clock work by day and night teams of actuaries.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] In the 1930s and 1940s, the mathematical foundations for stochastic processes were developed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] Actuaries could now begin to estimate losses using models of random events, instead of the deterministic methods they had used in the past.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] The introduction and development of the computer further revolutionized the actuarial profession.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuarial-science] From pencil-and-paper to punchcards to current high-speed devices, the modeling and forecasting ability of the actuary has rapidly improved while still being heavily dependent on the assumptions input into the models; actuaries have needed to adjust to this new world.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] An **actuary** is a professional with advanced mathematical skills who deals with the measurement and management of risk and uncertainty.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] These risks can affect both sides of the balance sheet and require asset management, liability management, and valuation skills.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries provide assessments of financial security systems, with a focus on their complexity, their mathematics, and their mechanisms.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The name of the corresponding academic discipline is actuarial science.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] While the concept of insurance dates to antiquity, the concepts needed to scientifically measure and mitigate risks have their origins in 17th-century studies of probability and annuities.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The profession has consistently been ranked as one of the most desirable.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In various studies in the United States, being an actuary has been ranked first or second multiple times since 2010.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries use skills primarily in mathematics—particularly calculus-based probability and mathematical statistics—but also economics, computer science, finance, and business.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries assemble and analyze data to estimate the probability and likely cost of an event such as death, sickness, injury, disability, or property loss.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries also answer financial questions: these questions include the level of pension contributions needed to produce a certain retirement income, and how a company should invest resources to maximize the return on investment in light of potential risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Using broad knowledge, actuaries help to design and price insurance policies, pension plans, and other financial strategies so as to ensure that the plans are maintained on a sound financial basis.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Most traditional actuarial disciplines fall into two main categories: life and non-life.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Life actuaries, who include health and pension actuaries, primarily deal with three kinds of risk: mortality, morbidity, and investment.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Products prominent in their work include life insurance, annuities, pensions, short and long term disability insurance, health insurance, health savings accounts, and long-term care insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In addition to actuarial risks, social insurance programs are influenced by public opinion, politics, budget constraints, changing demographics, and other factors such as medical technology, inflation, and cost of living considerations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Non-life actuaries, also known as "property and casualty" (mainly US) or "general insurance" (mainly UK) actuaries, deal with both physical and legal risks that affect people or their property.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Products prominent in their work include auto insurance, homeowners insurance, commercial property insurance, workers' compensation, malpractice insurance, product liability insurance, marine insurance, terrorism insurance, and other types of liability insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries are also consulted for their expertise in enterprise risk management.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] This work may involve dynamic financial analysis, stress testing, the formulation of corporate risk policy, and the establishment and operation of corporate risk departments.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries are also involved in other areas of economics and finance, such as analyzing securities offerings or market research.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] For both life and casualty actuaries, their classic role is calculating premiums and reserves for insurance policies that cover various risks.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] On the casualty side, analysis often involves quantifying the probability of a loss event (called the frequency) and the size of that loss event (called the severity).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The amount of time occurring before the loss event is important, because the insurer will only need to pay after the event has occurred.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] On the life side, analysis often involves quantifying the worth of a potential sum of money or a financial liability at different times in the future.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Since neither of these analysis types is a purely deterministic process, stochastic models are often used to determine frequency and severity distributions, as well as the parameters of these distributions.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Forecasting interest yields and currency movements also plays a role in determining future costs, especially for life actuaries.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries do not always attempt to predict aggregate future events.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Often their work relates to determining the cost of financial liabilities that have already occurred, called retrospective reinsurance, or the development or re-pricing of new products.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries also design and maintain products and systems.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] They participate in financial reporting of companies' assets and liabilities.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries must communicate complex concepts to clients who may not share their language or depth of knowledge.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] They work under a code of ethics that covers their communications and work products.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] As an outgrowth of more traditional roles, actuaries also work in the fields of risk management and enterprise risk management for both financial and non-financial corporations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries in traditional roles study and use tools and data previously in the domain of finance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Two accords—the Basel II accord for financial institutions (2004), and the analogous Solvency II accord for insurance companies (in force since 2016)—require institutions to account for operational risk separately, in addition to credit, reserve, asset, and insolvency risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuarial skills are well suited to this context, because actuaries are trained in analyzing various forms of risk, and judging the potential for gain and loss associated with these forms of risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries also participate in investment advising and asset management, and can be general business managers and chief financial officers or chief investment officers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] They analyze business prospects using financial skills in valuing or discounting risky future cash flows; they also apply pricing expertise in insurance to other lines of business.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] For example, insurance securitization requires both actuarial and finance skills.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries also act as expert witnesses in court trials, by using analysis to estimate the economic value of losses such as lost profits or lost wages.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The basic requirements of communal interests gave rise to risk sharing since the dawn of civilization.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] For example, people who lived their entire lives in a camp had the risk of fire, which would leave their band or family without shelter.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] After barter came into existence, more complex risks emerged and new forms of risk manifested.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Merchants embarking on trade journeys bore the risk of losing goods entrusted to them, their own possessions, or even their lives.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Intermediaries developed to warehouse and trade goods, which exposed them to financial risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The primary providers in extended families or households ran the risk of premature death, disability or infirmity, which could leave their dependents to starve.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Credit procurement was difficult if the creditor worried about repayment in the event of the borrower's death or infirmity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Alternatively, people sometimes lived too long from a financial perspective, exhausting their savings, if any, or becoming a burden on others in the extended family or society.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the ancient world there was not always room for the sick, suffering, disabled, aged, or the poor—these were often not part of the cultural consciousness of societies.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Early methods of protection, aside from the normal support of the extended family, involved charity; religious organizations or neighbors would collect for the destitute and needy.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] By the middle of the 3rd century, charitable operations in Rome supported 1,500 suffering people.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Charitable protection remains an active form of support in the modern era, but receiving charity is uncertain and often accompanied by social stigma.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Elementary mutual aid agreements and pensions did arise in antiquity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] These societies sometimes sold shares in the building of columbāria, or burial vaults, owned by the fund.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Non-life insurance started as a hedge against loss of cargo during sea travel.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Anecdotal reports of such guarantees occur in the writings of Demosthenes, who lived in the 4th century BCE.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The earliest records of an official non-life insurance policy come from Sicily, where there is record of a 14th-century contract to insure a shipment of wheat.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In 1350, Lenardo Cattaneo assumed "all risks from act of God, or of man, and from perils of the sea" that may occur to a shipment of wheat from Sicily to Tunis up to a maximum of 300 florins.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] During the 17th century, a more scientific basis for risk management was being developed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In 1662, a London draper named John Graunt showed that there were predictable patterns of longevity and death in a defined group, or cohort, of people, despite the uncertainty about the future longevity or mortality of any one individual.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The first person to correctly calculate these values was Edmond Halley.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In his work, Halley demonstrated a method of using his life table to calculate the premium someone of a given age should pay to purchase a life-annuity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] James Dodson's pioneering work on the level premium system led to the formation of the Society for Equitable Assurances on Lives and Survivorship (now commonly known as Equitable Life) in London in 1762.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] This was the first life insurance company to use premium rates that were calculated scientifically for long-term life policies, using Dodson's work.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] After Dodson's death in 1757, Edward Rowe Mores took over the leadership of the group that eventually became the Society for Equitable Assurances.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] It was he who specified that the chief official should be called an *actuary*.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Previously, the use of the term had been restricted to an official who recorded the decisions, or *acts*, of ecclesiastical courts, in ancient times originally the secretary of the Roman senate, responsible for compiling the *Acta Senatus*.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Other companies that did not originally use such mathematical and scientific methods most often failed or were forced to adopt the methods pioneered by Equitable.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the 18th and 19th centuries, computational complexity was limited to manual calculations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The calculations required to compute fair insurance premiums can be burdensome.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The actuaries of that time developed methods to construct easily used tables, using arithmetical short-cuts called commutation functions, to facilitate timely, accurate, manual calculations of premiums.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the mid-19th century, professional bodies were founded to support and further both actuaries and actuarial science, and to protect the public interest by ensuring competency and ethical standards.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Since calculations were cumbersome, actuarial shortcuts were commonplace.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Non-life actuaries followed in the footsteps of their life compatriots in the early 20th century.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the United States, the 1920 revision to workers' compensation rates took over two months of around-the-clock work by day and night teams of actuaries.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the 1930s and 1940s, rigorous mathematical foundations for stochastic processes were developed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries began to forecast losses using models of random events instead of deterministic methods.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Computers further revolutionized the actuarial profession.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] From pencil-and-paper to punchcards to microcomputers, the modeling and forecasting ability of the actuary has grown vastly.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Another modern development is the convergence of modern finance theory with actuarial science.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the early 20th century, some economists and actuaries were developing techniques that can be found in modern financial theory, but for various historical reasons, these developments did not achieve much recognition.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the 21st century, the profession, both in practice and in the educational syllabi of many actuarial organizations, combines tables, loss models, stochastic methods, and financial theory, but is still not completely aligned with modern financial economics.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] As there are relatively few actuaries in the world compared to other professions, actuaries are in high demand, and are highly paid for the services they render.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The actuarial profession has been ranked among the more desirable occupations in various surveys over time.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries typically work standard professional hours in office-based environments and are employed across sectors such as insurance, finance, and consulting.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The profession is generally associated with relatively high compensation and stable employment prospects.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] It has also been identified in some studies and rankings as a strong profession for women, and as relatively resilient during economic downturns.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Becoming a fully credentialed actuary requires passing a rigorous series of professional examinations, usually taking several years.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In some countries, such as Denmark, most study takes place in a university setting.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In others, such as the US, most study takes place during employment through a series of examinations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the UK, and countries based on its process, there is a hybrid university-exam structure.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] In the UK, a **chartered actuary** is a qualified member of the Institute and Faculty of Actuaries (IFoA).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] This title signifies that the holder has passed rigorous professional exams and adheres to the IFoA's standards of practice and ethics.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Members can use the titles Chartered Actuary (Associate) or Chartered Actuary (Fellow).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The chartered actuary designation enhances public trust by distinguishing qualified actuaries from those who may not have met the same educational and professional standards.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] As these qualifying exams are extremely rigorous, support is usually available to people progressing through the exams.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Often, employers provide paid on-the-job study time and paid attendance at seminars designed for the exams.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Also, many companies that employ actuaries have automatic pay raises or promotions when exams are passed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] As a result, actuarial students have strong incentives for devoting adequate study time during off-work hours.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] A common rule of thumb for exam students is that, for the Society of Actuaries examinations, roughly 400 hours of study time are necessary for each four-hour exam.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Thus, thousands of hours of study time should be anticipated over several years, assuming no failures.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Historically, the actuarial profession has been reluctant to specify the pass marks for its examinations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] To address concerns that there are pre-existing pass/fail quotas, a former chairman of the Board of Examiners of the Institute and Faculty of Actuaries stated: "Although students find it hard to believe, the Board of Examiners does not have fail quotas to achieve.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Accordingly, pass rates are free to vary (and do).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] They are determined by the quality of the candidates sitting the examination and in particular how well prepared they are.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Fitness to pass is the criterion, not whether you can achieve a mark in the top 40% of candidates sitting." In 2000, the Casualty Actuarial Society (CAS) decided to start releasing pass marks for the exams it offers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] The CAS's policy is also not to grade to specific pass ratios; the CAS board affirmed in 2001 that "the CAS shall use no predetermined pass ratio as a guideline for setting the pass mark for any examination.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] If the CAS determines that 70% of all candidates have demonstrated sufficient grasp of the syllabus material, then those 70% should pass.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Early American mathematician remembered for his work on ocean navigation.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Cramér was an Honorary President of the Swedish Actuarial Society.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Italian statistician and actuary renowned for his foundational work in subjective probability theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] He was the founding President of the Italian Central Institute of Statistics in 1926 and set up first the School and then the faculty of statistics, demographic and actuarial sciences in Roma in 1936.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Head of the Royal Mathematical School, and Stone's School, Dodson built on the statistical mortality tables developed by Edmund Halley in 1693.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] While Halley actually predated much of what is now considered the start of the actuarial profession, he was the first to rigorously calculate premiums for a life insurance policy mathematically and statistically.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] American actuarial educator, researcher, and author.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Lundberg is considered one of the founders of mathematical risk theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] First person to use the title 'actuary' with respect to a business position.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Morgan was the appointed Actuary of the Society for Equitable Assurances in 1775.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] He expanded on Mores's and Dodson's work, and may be considered the father of the actuarial profession in that his title became applied to the field as a whole.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] American actuary who was instrumental in the creation of the U.S.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] British actuary who developed the Redington Immunization Theory.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] American actuary and abolitionist, professor of mathematics at Western Reserve College (Ohio).
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] He campaigned for laws that required life insurance companies to hold sufficient reserves to guarantee that policies would be paid.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] Actuaries have appeared in works of fiction including literature, theater, television, and film.
[src:actuarial-modeling/actuary] At times, they have been portrayed as "math-obsessed, socially disconnected individuals with shockingly bad comb-overs", which has resulted in a mixed response amongst actuaries themselves.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In actuarial science and demography, a **life table** (also called a **mortality table** or **actuarial table**) is a table which shows, for each age, the probability that a person of that age will die before their next birthday ("probability of death").
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In other words, it represents the survivorship of people from a certain population.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] They can also be explained as a long-term mathematical way to measure a population's longevity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Tables have been created by demographers including John Graunt, Reed and Merrell, Nathan Keyfitz, and Thomas N.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] There are two types of life tables used in actuarial science.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The period life table represents mortality rates during a specific time period for a certain population.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] A cohort life table, often referred to as a generation life table, is used to represent the overall mortality rates of a certain population's entire lifetime.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] They must have had to be born during the same specific time interval.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] A cohort life table is more frequently used because it is able to make a prediction of any expected changes in the mortality rates of a population in the future.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] This type of table also analyzes patterns in mortality rates that can be observed over time.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Both of these types of life tables are created based on an actual population from the present, as well as an educated prediction of the experience of a population in the near future.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In order to find the true life expectancy average, 100 years would need to pass and by then finding that data would be of no use as healthcare is continually advancing.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Other life tables in historical demography may be based on historical records, although these often undercount infants and understate infant mortality, on comparison with other regions with better records, and on mathematical adjustments for varying mortality levels and life expectancies at birth.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] From this starting point, a number of inferences can be derived.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Life tables are also used extensively in biology and epidemiology.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] An area that uses this tool is Social Security.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] It examines the mortality rates of all the people who have Social Security to decide which actions to take.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The concept is also of importance in product life cycle management.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] All mortality tables are specific to environmental and life circumstances, and are used to probabilistically determine expected maximum age within those environmental conditions.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] allows study of life expectancy as a function of age already achieved.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Static life tables sample individuals assuming a stationary population with overlapping generations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] "Static life tables" and "cohort life tables" will be identical if population is in equilibrium and environment does not change.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] If a population were to have a constant number of people each year, it would mean that the probabilities of death from the life table were completely accurate.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Also, an exact number of 100,000 people were born each year with no immigration or emigration involved.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] "Life table" primarily refers to *period* life tables, as cohort life tables can only be constructed using data up to the current point, and distant projections for future mortality.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Life tables can be constructed using projections of future mortality rates, but more often they are a snapshot of age-specific mortality rates in the recent past, and do not necessarily purport to be projections.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] A life table is created by mortality rates and census figures from a certain population, ideally under a closed demographic system.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] This means that immigration and emigration do not exist when analyzing a cohort.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] A closed demographic system assumes that migration flows are random and not significant, and that immigrants from other populations have the same risk of death as an individual from the new population.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Another benefit from mortality tables is that they can be used to make predictions on demographics or different populations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] However, there are also weaknesses of the information displayed on life tables.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] One being that they do not state the overall health of the population.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] There is more than one disease present in the world, and a person can have more than one disease at different stages simultaneously, introducing the term comorbidity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Therefore, life tables also do not show the direct correlation of mortality and morbidity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The life table observes the mortality experience of a single generation, consisting of 100,000 births, at every age number they can live through.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Life tables are usually constructed separately for men and for women because of their substantially different mortality rates.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Other characteristics can also be used to distinguish different risks, such as smoking status, occupation, and socioeconomic class.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Life tables can be extended to include other information in addition to mortality, for instance health information to calculate health expectancy.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Health expectancies such as disability-adjusted life year and Healthy Life Years are the remaining number of years a person can expect to live in a specific health state, such as free of disability.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Life tables that relate to maternal deaths and infant moralities are important, as they help form family planning programs that work with particular populations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] They also help compare a country's average life expectancy with other countries.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Comparing life expectancy globally helps countries understand why one country's life expectancy is rising substantially by looking at each other's healthcare, and adopting ideas to their own systems.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In order to price insurance products, and ensure the solvency of insurance companies through adequate reserves, actuaries must develop projections of future insured events (such as death, sickness, and disability).
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] To do this, actuaries develop mathematical models of the rates and timing of the events.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] An actuary's job is to form a comparison between people at risk of death and people who actually died to come up with a probability of death for a person at each age number, defined as qx in an equation.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] When analyzing a population, one of the main sources used to gather the required information is insurance by obtaining individual records that belong to a specific population.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] These are called mortality tables if they show death rates, and morbidity tables if they show various types of sickness or disability rates.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] This is particularly the case in non-life insurance (e.g. the pricing of motor insurance can allow for a large number of risk factors, which requires a correspondingly complex table of expected claim rates).
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] However the expression "life table" normally refers to human survival rates and is not relevant to non-life insurance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The basic algebra used in life tables is as follows.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] This symbol refers to central rate of mortality.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] It is approximately equal to the average force of mortality, averaged over the year of age.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Further descriptions: The variable dx stands for the number of deaths that would occur within two consecutive age numbers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] An example of this is the number of deaths in a cohort that were recorded between the age of seven and the age of eight.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The variable *ℓx*, which stands for the opposite of *dx*, represents the number of people who lived between two consecutive age numbers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The variable *Tx* stands for the years lived beyond each age number x by all members in the generation.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] *Ėx* represents the life expectancy for members already at a specific age number.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In practice, it is useful to have an ultimate age associated with a mortality table.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Once the ultimate age is reached, the mortality rate is assumed to be 1.000.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] This age may be the point at which life insurance benefits are paid to a survivor or annuity payments cease.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] In epidemiology and public health, both standard life tables (used to calculate life expectancy), as well as the Sullivan and multi-state life tables (used to calculate health expectancy)**,** are the most commonly mathematical used devices.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] The latter includes information on health in addition to mortality.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] By watching over the life expectancy of any year(s) being studied, epidemiologists can see if diseases are contributing to the overall increase in mortality rates.
[src:actuarial-modeling/life-table] Epidemiologists are able to help demographers understand the sudden decline of life expectancy by linking it to the health problems that are arising in certain populations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] In financial accounting, **reserve** always has a credit balance and can refer to a part of shareholders' equity, a liability for estimated claims, or contra-asset for uncollectible accounts.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] A reserve can appear in any part of shareholders' equity except for contributed or basic share capital.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] In nonprofit accounting, an "operating reserve" is the unrestricted cash on hand available to sustain an organization, and nonprofit boards usually specify a target of maintaining several months of operating cash or a percentage of their annual income, called an **operating reserve ratio**.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] There are different types of reserves used in financial accounting, including capital reserves, revenue reserves, statutory reserves, realized reserves, unrealized reserves.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Reserve is the profit achieved by a company where a certain amount of it is put back into the business which can help the business in their rainy days.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] The preceding sentence may give the unwary reader the sense that this item is an asset, a debit balance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Retained Earnings typically has a credit balance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] If a firm wants to label part of Retained Earnings as a Reserve for Reinvestment, then that labeling does not harm, but neither does it do anything about making assets, liquid or otherwise, available for any day, rainy or otherwise.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Sometimes *reserve* is used in the sense of *provision*.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] This is inconsistent with the terminology suggested by International Accounting Standards Board.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] For more information about provisions, see provision (accounting).
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] The preceding is, indeed, correct IASB usage, but be aware in the U.S., under U.S.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Generally Accepted Accounting Principles, "provision" refers to a debit balance, not a credit balance.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] "Provision" is a dangerous word to use in attempting to achieve clear communications in conversations with U.S. and IASB conversations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] "Provision for Income Taxes" means expense in U.S.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] There is no single ideal operating reserve ratio.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] The purpose of the reserve is to keep the organization intact and to continue providing services during a temporary financial shock.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] The reserves need to be large enough to support all normal operating activities during an unexpected decline in income.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] A large organization that has a steady, reliable income source is unlikely to burn through more than about three months' expenses during an unexpected financial shock.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] A smaller organization (e.g., less than US$1,000,000 per year) or one with volatile income sources could be vulnerable even if it had more than six months' expenses in reserve.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Grantmakers, for example, frequently maintain operating reserves of more than 12 months because their income often depends on a volatile stock market.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] A large animal protection organization has about a 10% chance of losing a quarter of their revenue during a year, which would require about three months' reserves to cover, and a 1% risk of losing half their revenue during a difficult year, which would require reserves equal to six months' expenses.
[src:actuarial-modeling/reserve-accounting] Small animal protection organizations have more volatile income patterns, so they need higher reserves, potentially exceeding more than a year's worth of expenses.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] In actuarial science and applied probability, **ruin theory** (sometimes **risk theory** or **collective risk theory**) uses mathematical models to describe an insurer's vulnerability to insolvency/ruin.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] In such models key quantities of interest are the probability of ruin, distribution of surplus immediately prior to ruin, and deficit at time of ruin.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The theoretical foundation of ruin theory, known as the Cramér–Lundberg model (or classical compound-Poisson risk model, classical risk process or Poisson risk process) was introduced in 1903 by the Swedish actuary Filip Lundberg.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Lundberg's work was republished in the 1930s by Harald Cramér.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The model describes an insurance company who experiences two opposing cash flows: incoming cash premiums and outgoing claims.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The central object of the model is to investigate the probability that the insurer's surplus level eventually falls below zero (making the firm bankrupt).
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] where the time of ruin is $\tau =\inf\{t>0\,:\,X(t)<0\}$ with the convention that $\inf \varnothing =\infty$ .
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] and $\cdot ^{\ast n}$ denotes the n -fold convolution.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Assuming that the premium is equal to the expected loss, $c=\lambda \mu$ , we see that the company will ultimately run into insolvency with probability 1.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Sparre Andersen extended the classical model in 1957 by allowing claim inter-arrival times to have arbitrary distribution functions.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] where the claim number process $(N_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a renewal process and $(\xi _{i})_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ are independent and identically distributed random variables.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The model furthermore assumes that $\xi _{i}>0$ almost surely and that $(N_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ and $(\xi _{i})_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ are independent.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The model is also known as the renewal risk model.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Powers and Gerber and Shiu analyzed the behavior of the insurer's surplus through the **expected discounted penalty function**, which is commonly referred to as Gerber-Shiu function in the ruin literature and named after actuarial scientists Elias S.W.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] It is arguable whether the function should have been called Powers-Gerber-Shiu function due to the contribution of Powers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] where $\delta$ is the discounting force of interest, $K_{\tau }$ is a general penalty function reflecting the economic costs to the insurer at the time of ruin, and the expectation $\mathbb {E} ^{x}$ corresponds to the probability measure $\mathbb {P} ^{x}$ .
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] The function is called expected discounted cost of insolvency by Powers.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Here the indicator function $\mathbb {I} (\tau <\infty )$ emphasizes that the penalty is exercised only when ruin occurs.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] It is quite intuitive to interpret the expected discounted penalty function.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Since the function measures the actuarial present value of the penalty that occurs at $\tau$ , the penalty function is multiplied by the discounting factor $e^{-\delta \tau }$ , and then averaged over the probability distribution of the waiting time to $\tau$ .
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] While Gerber and Shiu applied this function to the classical compound-Poisson model, Powers argued that an insurer's surplus is better modeled by a family of diffusion processes.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] There are a great variety of ruin-related quantities that fall into the category of the expected discounted penalty function.
[src:actuarial-modeling/ruin-theory] Other finance-related quantities belonging to the class of the expected discounted penalty function include the perpetual American put option, the contingent claim at optimal exercise time, and more.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Following an EU Parliament vote on the Omnibus II Directive on 11 March 2014, Solvency II came into effect on 1 January 2016.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] This date had been previously pushed back many times.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The framework was substantially revised by Directive (EU) 2025/2, adopted in November 2024, which introduced new capital calibrations, proportionality arrangements for smaller insurers, and mandatory integration of climate and sustainability risks.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Member states must transpose the revised directive by 30 January 2027.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] EU insurance legislation aims to unify a single EU insurance market and enhance consumer protection.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The third-generation Insurance Directives established an "EU passport" (single licence) for insurers to operate in all member states if they fulfilled EU conditions.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Many member states concluded the EU minima were not enough, and took up their own reforms, which still led to differing regulations, hampering the goal of a single market.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] A number of the large Life Insurers in the UK are unhappy with the way the legislation has been developed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] In particular, concerns have been publicly expressed over a number of years by the CEO of Prudential, the UK's largest Life Insurance company.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Following Brexit, the United Kingdom implemented its own framework, known as Solvency UK, which took full effect at 31 December 2024.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The Prudential Regulation Authority relaxed the Matching Adjustment rules to allow insurers to hold more illiquid long-term assets such as infrastructure debt, and proposed the Matching Adjustment Accelerator in April 2025.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The divergence between Solvency UK and the revised EU directive has prompted debate among EU-based insurers about competitive disparities in capital deployment.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Since Directive 73/239/EEC was introduced in 1973, more elaborate risk management systems developed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Solvency II reflects new risk management practices to define required capital and manage risk.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] While the "Solvency I" Directive was aimed at revising and updating the current EU Solvency regime, Solvency II has a much wider scope.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Often called "Basel for insurers," Solvency II is somewhat similar to the banking regulations of Basel II.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The pillar 1 framework set out qualitative and quantitative requirements for calculation of technical provisions and Solvency Capital Requirement (SCR) using either a standard formula given by the regulators or an internal model developed by the (re)insurance company.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Technical provisions are divided on claim provisions, pertaining to earned business and premium provisions, pertaining to unearned business.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Premium provisions are not equal to unearned premium reserve.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The value of technical provision should be equal to the sum of best estimate of the liabilities and risk margin.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The best estimate corresponds to the probability-weighted average of future cash-flows, taking into account the time value of money.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Usage of central actuarial estimate is required and no margin for prudence is allowed.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Only cash-flows that are within contract boundaries are taken into consideration.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Solvency II specifies exact rules for determination of these contract boundaries.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Technical provisions represent the current amount the (re)insurance company would have to pay for an immediate transfer of its obligations to a third party.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The SCR is the capital required to ensure that the (re)insurance company will be able to meet its obligations over the next 12 months with a probability of at least 99.5%.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] In addition to the SCR capital a Minimum capital requirement (MCR) must be calculated which represents the threshold below which the national supervisor (regulator) would intervene.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The MCR is intended to correspond to an 85% probability of adequacy over a one-year period and is bounded between 25% and 45% of the SCR.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] For supervisory purposes, the SCR and MCR can be regarded as "soft" and "hard" floors respectively.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] That is, a regulatory ladder of intervention applies once the capital holding of the (re)insurance undertaking falls below the SCR, with the intervention becoming progressively more intense as the capital holding approaches the MCR.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The Solvency II Directive provides regional supervisors with a number of discretions to address breaches of the MCR, including the withdrawal of authorization from selling new business and the winding up of the company.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Directive (EU) 2025/2, formally adopted by the European Parliament and Council in November 2024, is the first comprehensive revision of the Solvency II framework since its entry into force in 2016.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The revised directive amends the original 2009 text across several material dimensions and must be transposed by all EU member states by 30 January 2027, with the amended delegated regulations entering application from January 2027.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The revision also mandates integration of sustainability and climate risks into the standard formula for the first time, reflecting recommendations from the EIOPA opinion on supervisory convergence for climate-related risks published in 2023.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] A significant proportionality innovation in the 2025 revision is the introduction of "small and non-complex enterprises" (SNCE) status, available to insurance undertakings below EUR 100 million in gross premium volume with limited cross-border activity.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] SNCE-status insurers benefit from reduced reporting obligations, including elimination of the regular supervisory report and simplified quarterly reporting templates.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Academic analysis of the proportionality principle in Solvency II has noted the tension between maintaining meaningful supervisory standards and reducing the compliance burden on smaller mutuals and cooperatives across Europe.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] National supervisory authorities have developed mandatory climate stress testing methodologies in advance of the 2025 revision's formal transposition.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] These projections do not imply that French insurers face near-term solvency risk, as the aggregate solvency ratio stood at 241 percent at end-June 2025, but they indicate that smaller insurers with solvency ratios near the regulatory floor face heightened risk under the revised climate calibrations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] EIOPA coordinates climate stress testing across the European Economic Area through its Union-wide stress test programme.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The 2023 EIOPA stress test incorporated a "sudden repricing" scenario in which a disorderly climate transition produces simultaneous shocks to interest rates, credit spreads, and equity values.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The results identified concentrations of climate-sensitive assets in life insurance portfolios across several member states, and informed the calibration choices subsequently embedded in Directive (EU) 2025/2.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Think-tanks such as the World Pensions & Investments Forum have argued that European legislators pushed dogmatically and naïvely for the adoption of the Basel II and **Solvency II** recommendations.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] In essence, they forced private banks, central banks, insurance companies and their regulators to rely more on assessments of credit risk by private rating agencies.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Thus, part of the public regulatory authority was abdicated in favor of private rating agencies.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The demanding nature of Solvency II legislation compared to current regulations has attracted criticism.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] According to RIMES, complying with the new legislation will impose a complex and significant burden on many European financial organizations, with 75% of firms in 2011 reporting that they were not in a position to comply with Pillar III reporting requirements.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The Matching adjustment mechanism of Solvency II has also been criticised as a form of creative accounting that hides the real value of liabilities.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Academic research has raised concerns about the procyclical effects of Solvency II's market-consistent valuation approach.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] Jørgensen, Davidoff, and Perotti (2017) demonstrated that mark-to-market capital requirements can amplify asset price volatility by forcing insurers into simultaneous asset sales during downturns, a dynamic not present under the prior Solvency I regime based on book-value accounting.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The compliance cost burden has been identified as a structural disadvantage for small and medium-sized mutuals.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] A study by McKinsey and Company estimated that full Solvency II compliance requires annual expenditure equivalent to 3 to 5 percent of premiums for smaller insurers, compared with under 1 percent for large groups that can amortize systems and governance costs over a larger premium base.
[src:actuarial-modeling/solvency-ii] The introduction of SNCE proportionality status in Directive (EU) 2025/2 is intended to partially address this concern, though critics note that the EUR 100 million threshold excludes the majority of mid-sized European mutuals that face the highest relative compliance burden.
